The <b>Russet Nightingale-Thrush</b> (<i>Catharus occidentalis</i>) is a species of <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bird" title="Bird">bird</a> in the <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Turdidae" title="Turdidae" class="mw-redirect">Turdidae</a> family. It is <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Endemism" title="Endemism">endemic</a> to <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mexico" title="Mexico">Mexico</a>.
Its natural <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Habitat" title="Habitat">habitat</a> is subtropical or tropical moist <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Montane_forest" title="Montane forest" class="mw-redirect">montane forests</a>.
Crown, back and wings brown. Face pale gray. Throat and belly pale gray, washed dusky. Breast pale gray mottled dusky. Juveniles more strongly mottled on breast and sides. Very similar to <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ruddy-capped_Nightingale-thrush" title="Ruddy-capped Nightingale-thrush" class="mw-redirect">Ruddy-capped Nightingale-thrush</a>. Tell apart from song or in flight by yellow bar on the secondary feathers below the wing, present only in the Russet Nightingale-thrush.
